## Threading Model

### Variant Loading (Parallel)

Each variant block can be loaded independently by separate threads.
Use DuckDB's per-thread local state pattern:

- **GlobalState**: atomic variant block counter, shared accumulation
  matrices (G1, G2, QQ, BB) protected by mutex for merge.
- **LocalState**: per-thread pgenlib reader, per-thread partial
  accumulation buffers, genovec decode buffer.

Each thread:
1. Claims a variant block via atomic fetch-add
2. Loads genotypes via its own PgenReader
3. Normalizes and accumulates into thread-local partial matrix
4. Merges into global accumulator under mutex (or lock-free via
   per-thread partials merged after pass completion)

**Preferred**: Per-thread partial matrices merged after each pass
completes (same pattern as `plink_score`). Avoids mutex contention
during the hot loop.

### SVD (Single-threaded Eigen3)

Eigen3 BDCSVD runs single-threaded on the small Krylov/projection
matrices. This is O(N × qq_col_ct²) and takes negligible time compared
to the genotype streaming passes.

If performance profiling shows SVD as a bottleneck (unlikely), Eigen3
can be compiled with OpenBLAS backend via `-DEIGEN_USE_BLAS` without
code changes.

---

## Dependency: Eigen3

Header-only C++ linear algebra library. No linking, no Fortran, no
runtime dependencies.

### Integration

**Recommended: vcpkg.** The DuckDB extension build system already has
full vcpkg support (toolchain, manifest merging, platform triplets).
Adding Eigen3 via vcpkg is a one-line manifest change and keeps the
dependency managed alongside the build:

```json
{
  "dependencies": ["eigen3"]
}
```

Alternative: vendor Eigen3 headers in `third_party/eigen3/` (~4MB,
MPL2-licensed). This avoids adding vcpkg as a new mechanism but adds
vendored code to the repo. The project already vendors plink-ng as a
submodule, so either approach has precedent.

### Usage

```cpp
#include <Eigen/Dense>
#include <Eigen/SVD>

// BDCSVD for tall-skinny Krylov matrix (M variants × qq_col_ct columns)
Eigen::Map<Eigen::MatrixXd> QQ(qq_data, M, qq_col_ct);
Eigen::BDCSVD<Eigen::MatrixXd> svd(QQ, Eigen::ComputeThinU | Eigen::ComputeThinV);
auto U = svd.matrixU();
auto S = svd.singularValues();
```

### Future: OpenBLAS Backend

If SVD becomes a bottleneck, add `-DEIGEN_USE_BLAS` and link OpenBLAS.
Zero code changes — Eigen3 delegates to BLAS automatically. OpenBLAS
available via vcpkg.

