## Scale Guidance

The dominant allocation is QQ (M × qq_col_ct doubles), which scales
with variant count. Per-thread g2/bb buffers (N × qq_col_ct each)
scale with sample count × thread count.

Memory formula (T = compute threads):
```
QQ:           M × qq_col_ct × 8 bytes
G1:           N × 2k × 8 bytes
g2_bb_parts:  N × qq_col_ct × 8 bytes × T
yy_bufs:      240 × T × N × 8 bytes × 2  (double-buffered)
y_transpose:  240 × N × 8 bytes × T
Total ≈ M × qq_col_ct × 8  +  N × qq_col_ct × 8 × T  +  small terms
```

| N (samples) | M (variants) | n_pcs | qq_col_ct | QQ (dominant) | g2/bb (T=4) | Total ~T=4 | Passes |
|-------------|-------------|-------|-----------|--------------|-------------|------------|--------|
| 1K | 100K | 10 | 220 | 176 MB | 7 MB | ~190 MB | 12 |
| 10K | 1M | 10 | 220 | 1.76 GB | 70 MB | ~2.1 GB | 12 |
| 50K | 1M | 10 | 220 | 1.76 GB | 352 MB | ~3.2 GB | 12 |
| 50K | 5M | 10 | 220 | 8.8 GB | 352 MB | ~9.9 GB | 12 |
| 50K | 5M | 20 | 840 | 33.6 GB | 1.34 GB | ~39 GB | 22 |
| 500K | 1M | 10 | 220 | 1.76 GB | 3.5 GB | ~16 GB | 12 |

Key observations:
- QQ dominates for high variant counts (which is the typical PCA case —
  many LD-pruned variants)
- g2/bb per-thread buffers dominate for very high sample counts with
  few variants (unusual)
- For large n_pcs (> 20), qq_col_ct grows quadratically — warn early

Consider reusing the `plinking_max_matrix_elements` config option as a
memory guard. The critical product is `M × qq_col_ct` (QQ allocation).

